import{Q as i}from"./QImg.b583f9bb.js";import{Q as o}from"./QMarkupTable.f7ab8644.js";import{_ as r}from"./plugin-vue_export-helper.21dcd24c.js";import{D as g,aM as d,bu as s,G as n,H as t,I as a,F as l,aX as u}from"./index.3f7a78fe.js";const h={class:"row justify-center no-wrap",style:{gap:"15px"}},p={class:"row justify-center no-wrap",style:{gap:"15px"}},f={class:"row justify-center no-wrap",style:{gap:"15px"}},m={class:"row justify-center no-wrap",style:{gap:"15px"}},y={class:"row justify-center no-wrap",style:{gap:"15px"}},w=Object.assign({name:"NfEffGuideArticle"},{__name:"NfEffGuideArticle",setup(b){return(v,e)=>(g(),d(u,null,[e[65]||(e[65]=s('<div class="foreword" data-v-d2d57a86><p class="foreword-title" data-v-d2d57a86>FOREWORD</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Welcome to the first article on my website. This article is very long and is intended for advanced minesweeper players. I&#39;d suggest that players who are not already familiar with the concept of efficiency or who have not won a no flag expert game may want to skip this article. I haven&#39;t yet decided what other articles I will make in the future, but I can guarantee they will be a lot shorter than this one, and will assume less prior knowledge. </p><br data-v-d2d57a86><p data-v-d2d57a86> Please be aware that this guide is also available on the <a href="https://minesweeper.online/help/guides" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>Minesweeper Online Guides</a> page as a <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1jTvFGb6XWyB-CaWb1EOri0I6LJ56m8NjcES2OfiLWjU" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>Google Doc</a>. I&#39;ve kept the wording of the Google Doc and the LlamaSweeper article exactly the same (only making changes to formatting), so please keep this context in mind as some parts may only make sense when read in the context of it being a Minesweeper Online guide. </p></div><p data-v-d2d57a86> I\u2019m Llama, a UK minesweeper player who has a lot of experience with no flag efficiency. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> In this document, I will be reviewing <a href="https://minesweeper.online/game/3192155452" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>this game</a> which is an 100% NF efficiency expert game I got during the March 2024 minesweeper.online championship. I hope to provide some insight into the decision making that goes on during an NF eff game. I\u2019ve included \u201Csemi-guide\u201D in the title since I will give extra information/explanations when I feel it is appropriate. There are other guides on NF efficiency, so I will skip over some of the theory that is already covered in those. I will assume a basic-to-intermediate understanding of NF efficiency. </p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Other guides</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Scar and PTTACGFans have made great guides for introducing NF efficiency </p><p data-v-d2d57a86><a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/401436" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>Basic No Flag Efficiency Guide</a> - Scar </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> PTT\u2019s guide is in Chinese, so I\u2019ve also included a link to a google translated version, however the translation likely has many mistakes </p><p data-v-d2d57a86><a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1NdMOCclwA6D_CSDV2T89OdxetuFYvwrqAVTkg8Pvds4/edit" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86> No Flag Efficiency guide </a> (Chinese) - PTTACGFans </p><p data-v-d2d57a86><a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/e/2PACX-1vRYT4eWK-bguktLx4aokAhmcS7PNk1zsR8DPEwZNh5DNsthAmXLhlwTsNom8xQzl87YVPO3DIS9N30k/pub" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86> Minesweeper tutorial for 100% NF efficiency </a> (translated to English) </p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Core NF Eff strategy</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Before I start the game review, I want to first go over some core strategy and principles that I use when playing. This section turned out to be quite long, so feel free to skip ahead. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86>Most moves fall into two different categories -</p><ul data-v-d2d57a86><li data-v-d2d57a86>Protected squares</li><li data-v-d2d57a86>Opening predictions</li></ul><p data-v-d2d57a86><span style="text-decoration:underline;" data-v-d2d57a86>Protected squares</span></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The foolproof way to tell if a square is protected is to look at the 8 surrounding squares and ask yourself - \u201Ccould this be an opening\u201D. If the answer is always no, then the square is protected. This works, however most of the time it is overkill. Instead, I look out for the below mine patterns (and rotations/reflections). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Here, dark grey indicates the area of the board that is already solved* and green represents the squares that are protected from being part of an opening. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',17)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image1.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[66]||(e[66]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[67]||(e[67]=t("p",null,[t("em",null," *The dark grey squares don\u2019t have to be exact, I\u2019ve just included them to help show that these mine patterns only protect from openings occurring in a particular direction (in the case of this diagram they protect from openings coming in from the top right). We still have to be careful when looking for possible openings coming from the other direction (in this case, the bottom left). ")],-1)),e[68]||(e[68]=t("p",null," Sometimes, a combination of the above patterns has to be used. For example, green here is protected, since both of the below combinations of mines are able to protect it. ",-1)),e[69]||(e[69]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image2.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[70]||(e[70]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[71]||(e[71]=t("p",null," It\u2019s good to get into the habit of always clicking all of the known-to-be-safe protected squares before taking any risks. ",-1)),e[72]||(e[72]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Opening predictions")],-1)),e[73]||(e[73]=t("p",null," There are some general rules/principles that can be used when deciding where to go for an opening prediction. The choice depends a lot on what the board looks like, so these rules can be broken when it makes sense to do so. ",-1)),t("ol",null,[t("li",null,[e[0]||(e[0]=t("strong",null,"The fewer tiles required for a square to be an opening, the better.",-1)),e[1]||(e[1]=a(" Green is better than cyan in the below screenshot as it requires ")),e[2]||(e[2]=t("strong",null,"4 squares",-1)),e[3]||(e[3]=a(" to be safe in order for it to be an opening whereas cyan requires ")),e[4]||(e[4]=t("strong",null,"6 squares",-1)),e[5]||(e[5]=a(" to be safe for this. ")),e[6]||(e[6]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image3.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[7]||(e[7]=t("p",null,null,-1))]),t("li",null,[e[8]||(e[8]=t("strong",null,"It is preferable to go for openings where the square you are clicking on is known to be safe.",-1)),e[9]||(e[9]=a(" Here, red is a known mine. Green is better than Cyan as it is known to be safe, so you avoid the [mine density]% risk of blasting. You may still lose a click if orange is a mine and cyan is an opening. However, this is an acceptable risk since the chance of this happening is less than [mine density]% since even if orange is a mine, you may still be saved if there are mines above it that prevent the opening. ")),e[10]||(e[10]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image4.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[11]||(e[11]=t("p",null,null,-1))]),t("li",null,[e[12]||(e[12]=t("strong",null,"It is preferable to go for moves that can be \u201Cpulled\u201D towards solved areas.",-1)),e[13]||(e[13]=a(" Green is better than cyan in the below screenshot. They both have the same chance of giving an opening, but if instead they open a number, then green would enable you to uncover the yellow squares, and locate the mine(s) that are blocking the opening, whereas cyan would just let you uncover the brown square, which isn\u2019t as useful. I will discuss \u201Cpulling\u201D more later on in the document. ")),e[14]||(e[14]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image5.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[15]||(e[15]=t("p",null,null,-1))]),t("li",null,[e[16]||(e[16]=t("strong",null,"Compare moves by thinking about where the mines and openings could be that would mess things up.",-1)),e[17]||(e[17]=a(" It\u2019s possible to go very far with this, as in theory, you could calculate all the different probabilities of situations that can arise, and use this to weigh up different opening predictions. Most of the time this isn\u2019t necessary. In the below screenshot, I consider the green and the cyan opening predictions. For the green prediction, I note that there are 2 (orange) squares that could lose a click if they contain a mine and white is an opening. For the cyan prediction, there are 4 (orange) squares that could lose a click if they have a mine. So, I would judge green to be better than cyan as there are more ways that cyan can waste a click. ")),e[18]||(e[18]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image6.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[19]||(e[19]=t("p",null,null,-1))]),e[24]||(e[24]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"Try to close down the board."),a(" This is quite a general principle, so I don\u2019t have a screenshot to go along with it. It\u2019s a good idea to try to approach regions of the board from all sides as this makes them easier to deal with. Openings have a slight tendency to travel along the edge of the board as they require 6 squares to be safe rather than the usual 9. You can use this to your advantage and try to enclose regions of the board. In practice, this can be quite hard to do as often you just have to go where the game takes you. ")],-1)),t("li",null,[e[20]||(e[20]=t("strong",null,"Think about the bigger picture.",-1)),e[21]||(e[21]=a(" I wasn\u2019t sure exactly how to phrase this principle, but it is important. Cyan here seems like a very natural opening prediction to make. However, it provides no additional information about the board, so it could be better approached from a different direction. If, after solving the rest of the board, we discover that brown is a mine, then cyan can no longer be an opening and we would save ourselves from having to take an unnecessary [mine density]% risk with cyan. This example is quite specific, however the principle applies in lots of different situations. Whenever you make a guess, think about how it improves the state of the board - will it help solve an important area of the board? Is it likely to lead to lots of progress or is it in a closed off area that is better left for minecount? ")),e[22]||(e[22]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image7.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[23]||(e[23]=t("p",null,null,-1))]),e[25]||(e[25]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"Don\u2019t forget about the edge of the board."),a(" In particular, I mean moves like in the screenshot below, it\u2019s easy to overlook them, but they can rescue you in difficult situations when nothing else looks good. ")],-1))]),e[74]||(e[74]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image8.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[75]||(e[75]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[76]||(e[76]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Probabilities of openings")],-1)),e[77]||(e[77]=t("p",null,[a(" I stole this table from a Dard "),t("a",{href:"https://youtu.be/jKRydA5zqzI?si=JItkJZ_i84LhWluw&t=369",target:"_blank"},"video"),a(" . It shows how likely it is for an opening to occur. So, if 3 cells are required to be safe for there to be an opening, then it will be an opening 50% of the time on expert. I\u2019d suggest having a quick look over the table to check it matches your intuition. ")],-1)),e[78]||(e[78]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image9.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[79]||(e[79]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>The mindset</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The mindset of no flag efficiency depends on what your goal is. If you are dead set on achieving expert 100%, then this will naturally lead to a different strategy than if you are aiming for, say, above 95%. When aiming for 100%, you should treat losing a click to an opening and clicking on a mine as being equivalent. They both require a reset. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> When aiming for 100%, you may find yourself going hours without having any close attempts, so I would encourage you to make the most of any attempts that look promising. This means slowing down to avoid misclicks/mistaken logic and carefully evaluating the order of which to play moves to minimise overall risk taken. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> I would encourage you to minecount towards the end of games whenever there is a chance that knowledge of the minecount may lead to making a different decision. I use the paint bucket tool in jspaint for this and I change colour every 10 mines. Remember that expert has 99 mines instead of 100, so if you are counting in 10s the last batch will have 9 mines - I\u2019ve made this mistake before. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> If we assume that expert NF 100% happens once per 50 hours of playtime, then taking an unnecessary 80% safe guess right at the end of a winning game will on average set you back by 10 hours. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> MSCoach has run some simulations with his solver on expert NF 100% Eff. He found that it won around 1 in 4,444 games using a 4-corner start (more info can be found on his <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/567348" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>profile</a> ). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> To give a comparison with intermediate - I can get 100% around 1 in every 7 games on intermediate when playing as carefully as possible. I once did this <a href="https://minesweeper.online/winstreak/1611609033" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>6 times in a row</a> ! </p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Start of the review</p><p data-v-d2d57a86>As a reminder, we will be reviewing this game</p><p data-v-d2d57a86><a href="https://minesweeper.online/game/3192155452" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>https://minesweeper.online/game/3192155452</a><br data-v-d2d57a86><br data-v-d2d57a86> It\u2019s a very slow game, so if you want to follow along, I\u2019d suggest using the replay stepper. If you have a premium account, this can be activated by enabling the \u201CAdvanced Replay\u201D in the settings. It gives extra buttons for skipping forward moves (left/right arrow keys also work). If you don\u2019t have a premium account then arrow keys should still work as long as \u201Cuse hotkeys\u201D is enabled in the settings. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86><br data-v-d2d57a86></p>',12)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image10.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[80]||(e[80]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[81]||(e[81]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image11.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[82]||(e[82]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[83]||(e[83]=t("p",null,[a(" I start out the game with 4 corners. I can\u2019t fully recommend this, as MSCoach\u2019s simulations suggest that aiming to get an opening in the middle before clicking the corners is better in the long run, at the cost of having to reset more often. In my other 100% "),t("a",{href:"https://minesweeper.online/game/801705135",target:"_blank"},"game"),a(" , I used this middle-opening-then-corners strategy. ")],-1)),e[84]||(e[84]=t("p",null," That said, there is some room for preference in starting strategy, some players may find having to reset for a middle opening to be less fun as only ~5% of games make it past the starting strategy (compared to 50% for just corners). I will note that during the April 2026 NF Eff Championship, many players went for just 4 corners or edge opening + 4 corners. One player told me that they clicked 4 corners and an edge and only reset if the edge click revealed a \u201C1\u201D (noting that a \u201C2\u201D can also lose clicks but they considered this an acceptable risk), this strategy may be a happy middle ground option. So given that NF Eff 100% games have been won with a variety of starting strategies, I can\u2019t give any hard recommendations other than to do 4 corners minimum. ",-1)),e[85]||(e[85]=t("p",null," Putting this all to one side - I have a nice start with an opening in each corner. In this case, I click green (screenshot above) and then cyan before cleaning up some protected squares. Green is slightly better than cyan since there might be a mine in orange (which loses a click if there is an opening). ",-1)),e[86]||(e[86]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image12.png",class:"base-img img-600 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[87]||(e[87]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[88]||(e[88]=t("p",null," After hitting some openings and cleaning up the protected squares, we end up with the above. Green here is the natural choice (safe click + only needs 3 squares to be an opening). This doesn\u2019t give the opening we wanted, so I\u2019ll focus on this area in the next few screenshots. ",-1)),e[89]||(e[89]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image13.png",class:"base-img img-400 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[90]||(e[90]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[91]||(e[91]=t("p",null," I\u2019ll refer to the above images by their numbers (1-4). In the last move, we were hoping to get an opening but ended up with a 1 (shown in purple in the first image). ",-1)),e[92]||(e[92]=t("ol",null,[t("li",null," The purple 1 could lose us a click. So, we should focus on this area. If orange is a mine and black is an opening, then we\u2019d lose a click. We know that the mine will be in the orange or yellow squares, and each of these will protect green, so we click green. "),t("li",null," Same idea as the previous step. The purple 1 is still at risk of losing a click, but green is protected by orange/yellow in either case, so we click green. "),t("li",null," We are in luck! As the last move revealed a 1, we know where the mine is, so there is no longer a risk of losing a click to an opening. "),t("li",null," We\u2019ve cleaned up the area and can go back to looking at the board as a whole ")],-1)),e[93]||(e[93]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image14.png",class:"base-img img-400 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[94]||(e[94]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[95]||(e[95]=t("p",null," Guessing green above is the natural and correct choice as it only requires the green square and 3 others to be safe in order to be an opening. There is also another advantage which is that the top region is very nice since we know all the yellow squares are safe, so we are likely to have good follow up moves after clicking the green square. ",-1)),e[96]||(e[96]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image15.png",class:"base-img img-500 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[97]||(e[97]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[98]||(e[98]=t("p",null," I skipped forwards a bit here as there wasn\u2019t much to say about the in-between guesses. We now have an obvious safe move here which is green. We also have to consider the orange region. Cyan seems like a natural guess to solve the orange region. However, the best decision is to leave the orange region until the end. It\u2019s a small closed off area, so if we leave it until the end and have a high number of mines remaining, then we will want to play safe rather than going for cyan. ",-1)),e[99]||(e[99]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"Preparation guesses",-1)),e[100]||(e[100]=t("p",null," Sometimes, in NF efficiency, there will be times where you may want to get more information about the board before going for an opening prediction. I want to cover a common example of this before going back to the review. ",-1)),e[101]||(e[101]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image16.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[102]||(e[102]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> We consider the above example, which happens to be from our game, but we will treat this as if it could be from any game (with any density). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86>You may ask - is it better to go for cyan or green?</p><p data-v-d2d57a86><span style="text-decoration:underline;" data-v-d2d57a86>Cyan</span></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Cyan is a guess with a [mine density]% chance of blasting (if you want to know why this is the case, you should watch Mine Buoy\u2019s <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=At8Kloh4KY4" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>video</a> on probability). The idea behind cyan is that it gives information on whether any of the grey squares contain a mine. If cyan reveals a 1, you can then click green (hoping for an opening), and if it reveals a 2 or 3 you will have to go for a backup guess somewhere else (such as the square immediately to the left of green). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86><span style="text-decoration:underline;" data-v-d2d57a86>Green</span></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The idea with green is that whilst it is more immediately risky, it means that you only need to take one guess instead of two. Green has a [mine density]% chance of blasting just like cyan, but it has extra risk posed by the grey squares, as if these contain a mine, then it\u2019s possible for green to be on the edge of an opening. Green also requires hoping for a less likely opening, this is because green being an opening requires 6 squares to be safe, whereas in the good case for cyan (that is where cyan reveals a 1) we only need 4 squares to be safe to give an opening. </p><br data-v-d2d57a86><br data-v-d2d57a86><p data-v-d2d57a86> I like to call guesses such as cyan \u201Cpreparation guesses\u201D because you are taking an additional risk in order to (hopefully) improve another guessing spot (in this case green). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> So, which is the better guess? Cyan or green? The answer is that it primarily depends on the board density. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> I\u2019ve done some rough calculations on green and cyan, which inform my following commentary on them. There is a section in the appendix where I go through my calculations and reasoning in depth. As a reminder, intermediate has 15.6% density, and expert has 20.6% density. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> For densities below 15%, you should choose cyan. This is because at lower densities, openings are more common, so the grey squares provide relatively more of a threat to the green guess. When the grey squares contain mines, it\u2019s quite likely that there will also be an opening to the left of green causing it to lose a click. It is worth going for cyan to remove the threat posed by the grey squares. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> For densities in the 15%-20%* range, things are less clear. Green wins out in short term survivability, but this is counteracted by the fact that cyan is more likely to lead to openings in the short term. I think both guesses are within a few percentage points of each other when combining these factors, so I can\u2019t outright say which is the better option. For intermediate, I tend to choose cyan, but for anything denser I tend to choose green as my playstyle is quite heavy on opening predictions (openings tend to give a lot of progress, and if a board doesn\u2019t have lots of openings, then it\u2019s a bad board). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> For densities in the 20%-25% range, you should click green because the high density means there isn\u2019t as much of a threat of it losing a click to the edge of an opening. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> For densities above 25%, you should start considering other options, such as playing safe in the hopes that there are no openings to bump into. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86><em data-v-d2d57a86> *I don\u2019t have an exact switching point as this depends on the trade-off between likelihood of surviving a guess and likelihood of getting an opening, which is hard to put a number on. </em></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> I\u2019d sum up my advice on preparation guesses as follows: look out for them, favour them on low densities or when the guess itself has low risk or gives a large amount of information, but be wary of the fact that you are taking an additional risk that may lead to no real progress. </p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Back to the review</p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',20)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image17.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[103]||(e[103]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[104]||(e[104]=t("p",null," We skip forwards again here. There isn\u2019t much to say about the intermediate guesses as they all fall into the category of clicking the square which is most likely to be an opening and then cleaning up afterwards when it isn\u2019t an opening. ",-1)),e[105]||(e[105]=t("p",null," We are now in a tricky spot. There are no good moves to make. The green guess is a wall click which requires the 6 squares in total to be safe in order to be an opening. It also is risky as there is a chance green is on the edge of an opening if either orange square is a mine. We still go for this wall click as it could give a lot of progress if it is an opening. Since it is on the edge, it is possible for the opening to travel along the edge of the board and help enclose it which would be very useful. ",-1)),e[106]||(e[106]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image18.png",class:"base-img img-500 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[107]||(e[107]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[108]||(e[108]=t("p",null," We are in a sticky situation again. If we are to play for an opening then any of the cyan squares will be natural choices. Perhaps the top-left cyan square would be the best guess of this nature. It was not the move I took. ",-1)),e[109]||(e[109]=t("p",null," I instead went for the green square, which is safe to click, but could be on the edge of an opening (e.g. if white was an opening). ",-1)),e[110]||(e[110]=t("p",null," In the context of aiming for 100%, this is a bad move. One way to see this is to look at the purple square to the left of green. Clicking purple will always be better than clicking green as there could be situations where green loses a click but purple doesn\u2019t. ",-1)),e[111]||(e[111]=t("p",null," So why did I go for the green square? The answer is that the game was played during the NF eff championship and I hadn\u2019t yet fully committed to going for 100%. The green square was an option that had no risk of blasting and would only lose a single click if the white square above was an opening. ",-1)),e[112]||(e[112]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image19.png",class:"base-img img-600 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[113]||(e[113]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[114]||(e[114]=t("p",null," Here, we have a few different options. We could guess cyan, or either green square. All 3 options are equally as likely to be an opening. Cyan is slightly safer than green when considering immediate risk as there are more ways that the green guesses could be on the edge of an opening. However, I discounted the cyan guess as it doesn\u2019t have good follow-up moves if it does not reveal an opening. ",-1)),e[115]||(e[115]=t("p",null," Both of the green guesses have good options if they do not reveal an opening. ",-1)),e[116]||(e[116]=t("p",null," In the case of guess A, we can reveal the yellow squares if we do not get an opening *. ",-1)),e[117]||(e[117]=t("p",null," In the case of guess B, we can reveal the yellow squares and also the brown squares *. ",-1)),e[118]||(e[118]=t("p",null,[t("em",null," * It may not be obvious why the yellow/brown squares can be clicked as follow-up squares. I explain more about the reasoning of this in the next section. ")],-1)),e[119]||(e[119]=t("p",null," So guess B is better as while it is equal to A in most ways, it lets us reveal more squares in the case where it doesn\u2019t reveal an opening. ",-1)),e[120]||(e[120]=t("p",null," For reasons I can\u2019t remember, but most likely because I was playing fast, I went for guess A, which gave a nice opening. ",-1)),e[121]||(e[121]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"}," Pulling and the rule of treating clicked squares as mines ",-1)),e[122]||(e[122]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image20.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[123]||(e[123]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[124]||(e[124]=t("p",null," Let\u2019s consider the above situation more closely, assuming that we just revealed the pink 1. ",-1)),e[125]||(e[125]=t("p",null," There is a mental shortcut that can be used in this situation which only applies when playing for 100% efficiency. The mental shortcut is that you can pretend that the square you clicked on is a mine. Here a clicked square refers to a square that was clicked on individually rather than being part of an opening. ",-1)),e[126]||(e[126]=t("p",null," I\u2019ll show this with diagrams first before explaining the logic behind this. ",-1)),e[127]||(e[127]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),t("div",h,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image21.png",class:"img-simple img-200 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"}),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image22.png",class:"img-simple img-200 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"})]),e[128]||(e[128]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[129]||(e[129]=t("p",null," First consider the image on the left. It should be easy to see in this case that the mines protect all the yellow squares. These squares cannot be part of an opening. ",-1)),e[130]||(e[130]=t("p",null," Now consider the image on the right. Using the mental shortcut, my claim is that the exact same yellow squares are still protected. This turns out to be true, but only under the assumption that we are playing for 100%. ",-1)),e[131]||(e[131]=t("p",null," Why does this work? One way to understand this is to realise that when we are going for 100%, mines and clicked squares interact with openings in the same way. The \u201Czero\u201D tile of an opening can never be next to a mine (because then it wouldn\u2019t be a \u201Czero\u201D tile). Similarly, the zero tile can never be next to a clicked square (purple in the diagram) as otherwise we would have already lost a click to an opening (which is equivalent to losing the game when going for 100%). ",-1)),e[132]||(e[132]=t("p",null," An alternate way to phrase this is - suppose we click on the yellow squares and they do happen to be on the edge of an opening losing us clicks, this would be acceptable as it means we have already lost a click with the clicked square (purple) so we were never going to get 100% on this board anyway. ",-1)),e[133]||(e[133]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"Back to the review",-1)),e[134]||(e[134]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image23.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[135]||(e[135]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[136]||(e[136]=t("p",null,"Here I would judge the guesses as follows:",-1)),e[137]||(e[137]=t("p",null," Cyan is safer as it is less likely to be touching an opening, but it is a bit out of the way and doesn\u2019t have very good follow-up moves if it doesn\u2019t give an opening. ",-1)),e[138]||(e[138]=t("p",null," Green is a bit riskier as there could be an opening above it or below-and-to-the-right of it. But green is more centre-of-the-action and has good follow-up moves. ",-1)),e[139]||(e[139]=t("p",null,"I chose green in this case, although both of these guesses are good.",-1)),e[140]||(e[140]=t("p",null," You may also ask the question - would the square directly above green be a good choice to click. I\u2019ll show below that the square directly above green has a notable disadvantage. ",-1)),e[141]||(e[141]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),t("div",p,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image24.png",class:"img-simple img-200 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"}),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image25.png",class:"img-simple img-200 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"})]),e[142]||(e[142]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[143]||(e[143]=t("p",null," The green guess and cyan guess both have 3* threatening openings (white and grey). These are places where bad openings could be that cause the guess to lose a click. However, cyan is slightly worse as the grey opening is more likely to happen for cyan than it is for green. The cyan-grey opening requires 6 safe squares to happen whilst the green-grey opening requires 9 safe squares to happen. ",-1)),e[144]||(e[144]=t("p",null,[t("em",null," * Technically, the white-right opening can be ignored as it\u2019s only possible for the white-right square to be an opening if white-left is also an opening. ")],-1)),e[145]||(e[145]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image26.png",class:"base-img img-400 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[146]||(e[146]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[147]||(e[147]=t("p",null," After cleaning up from the previous move which failed to yield an opening, we get the above. ",-1)),e[148]||(e[148]=t("p",null," The correct move for 100% is to click the green squares using the rule of \u201Ctreating clicked squares as mines\u201D. In this case, we\u2019d treat the purple square as the clicked square. ",-1)),e[149]||(e[149]=t("p",null," Instead, I ended up going for the cyan square. Why? I still wasn\u2019t fully committed to going for 100%. Whilst green is the correct for 100%, it is possible that it could transform a 1-click-loss situation into a multiple-click-loss situation. Also, the green squares don\u2019t give very good information. ",-1)),e[150]||(e[150]=t("p",null,"There are only two likely outcomes from playing the green squares:",-1)),e[151]||(e[151]=t("ul",null,[t("li",null,"We learn that we have wasted a click with purple"),t("li",null," We learn that we are still on track for 100% but haven\u2019t gained much information so we\u2019d still end up guessing cyan. ")],-1)),e[152]||(e[152]=t("p",null," So as the route to 100% is likely to involve guessing cyan, we might as well just guess it now. ",-1)),e[153]||(e[153]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image27.png",class:"base-img img-400 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[154]||(e[154]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[155]||(e[155]=t("p",null," Skipping ahead again, we have the above situation. Blue and cyan are all decent guesses although they all have the drawback of not having good follow-up moves in the cases where they don\u2019t lead to an opening. The blue squares are also quite far from other information, so may not give much progress even if they give a small opening. Cyan is slightly better than the blue options as it is closer to other information, so more likely to give good follow-up moves. ",-1)),e[156]||(e[156]=t("p",null," In this case I went for green as it is guaranteed to give information. Green has [mine density]% chance of blasting (just like the other options), but has very low risk of losing a click to an opening. ",-1)),e[157]||(e[157]=t("p",null," It\u2019s possible to estimate probabilities of certain risks to help judge them. The below diagram shows what would be required for green to lose a click to an opening. ",-1)),e[158]||(e[158]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image28.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[159]||(e[159]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p data-v-d2d57a86>The requirement for there to be a bad opening (white) is as follows:</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The top mine should be in orange (<span class="inline-maths" data-v-d2d57a86>\xBD</span> chance) </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The mines touching the 4 should be in orange (<span class="inline-maths" data-v-d2d57a86>\u2153</span> chance) </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Four floating cells should be safe (<span class="inline-maths" data-v-d2d57a86>1 - [mine density]</span> chance per safe cell). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> So the chance of this is <span class="inline-maths" data-v-d2d57a86>\xBD * \u2153 * (1 - [mine density])^4</span>. We can either manually minecount to get the mine density, or assume it is somewhere around 1 in 5 (20.625% on expert to be precise). Long story short, it is unlikely for green to lose a click to an opening (around 7% chance assuming normal density). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> So that should be the end of it, right? Green is equally as likely as the other options to be a mine but has good follow-up and very low risk of losing a click to an opening. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Some of you may have noticed that I haven\u2019t mentioned green square\u2019s twin. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',9)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image29.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[160]||(e[160]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[161]||(e[161]=t("p",null," The green square has a twin marked T above. The fact that green has a twin is another advantage of it that I didn\u2019t draw much attention to before. T gives useful information that either improves the cyan guess or tells us to go somewhere else. ",-1)),e[162]||(e[162]=t("p",null," Strictly speaking, I should\u2019ve clicked on T before I clicked on the left-green square. This is because T is part of the same guess as the left-green square, but is less exposed than it. Whenever left-green is safe, T will also be safe, but T doesn\u2019t have the risk of losing a click to an opening. ",-1)),e[163]||(e[163]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"High density strategy",-1)),e[164]||(e[164]=t("p",null," As you approach the end of the board, it is often sensible to work out what the remaining mine density is. The best way to play a high density endgame is often quite different from how you would play a low density endgame. I find high density strats to be one of the harder parts of NF efficiency. There is no exact percentage where \u201Chigh density\u201D starts - I usually start to consider high density strats as the density gets close to 25% and above. ",-1)),e[165]||(e[165]=t("p",null," I\u2019ve generated some typical 30x30 boards at different densities to give a rough idea of how these densities usually look. You should be able to see that openings start to make up much less of the board as the density increases. Openings are still reasonably common around the corners/edge of the board. I chose games close to the average 3bv for these boards, but the numbers given in the table will still differ from their true values. ",-1)),n(o,{flat:"",bordered:"","wrap-cells":"",separator:"cell",dense:"",class:"q-my-lg article-table"},{default:l(()=>[e[31]||(e[31]=t("colgroup",null,[t("col",{style:{width:"33.33%"}}),t("col",{style:{width:"33.33%"}}),t("col",{style:{width:"33.33%"}})],-1)),e[32]||(e[32]=t("thead",null,[t("tr",null,[t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"20% density")]),t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"25% density")]),t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"30% density")])])],-1)),t("tbody",null,[t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image30.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})]),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image31.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})]),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image32.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})])]),e[26]||(e[26]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"20%"),a(" mines (180) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"25%"),a(" mines (225) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"30%"),a(" mines (270) ")])],-1)),e[27]||(e[27]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"31%"),a(" protected squares (281) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"41%"),a(" protected squares (368) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"49%"),a(" protected squares (437) ")])],-1)),e[28]||(e[28]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"33%"),a(" opening edge squares (296) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"25%"),a(" opening edge squares (229) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"16%"),a(" opening edge squares (148) ")])],-1)),e[29]||(e[29]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"16%"),a(" \u201Czero\u201D squares (143) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"9%"),a(" \u201Czero\u201D squares (78) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"5%"),a(" \u201Czero\u201D squares (45) ")])],-1)),e[30]||(e[30]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"18.3"),a(" average size of an opening (including zeros and edges) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"14.0"),a(" average size of an opening (including zeros and edges) ")]),t("td",null,[t("strong",null,"12.9"),a(" average size of an opening (including zeros and edges) ")])],-1))])]),_:1}),e[166]||(e[166]=t("p",null," I will give some general tips about high density before returning to the review. ",-1)),e[167]||(e[167]=t("ul",null,[t("li",null," You should lean towards going for squares that are known to be safe, even if they have some risk of being on the edge of an opening. "),t("li",null," You should still be cautious around squares that are very likely to be openings (such as squares on the edge of the board). "),t("li",null," You should try to pick squares that give good information. Be aware that playing safely often gives less information than predicting openings, and may need multiple risks to be taken for the same amount of progress. "),t("li",null," Always think about how a move should be followed up. Before clicking any square, you should know where your next click will be for each possible number that could be revealed. "),t("li",null,[a(" Think about how your guesses affect the remaining density. This matters more when there aren\u2019t many squares/mines left. Guessing squares that touch many floating squares will give more knowledge about the remaining density. Also, playing for openings in one part of the board will make other parts of the board more dense on average. This is because if you get an opening in one part of the board, all the mines that could\u2019ve been blocking that opening now must be elsewhere. The reverse is also true, that playing for there to "),t("em",null,"not"),a(" be openings will reduce the density elsewhere. ")]),t("li",null," When playing safely, you may end up leaving some squares exposed to the risk of losing clicks. Keep track of these squares and avoid moves that increase the risk of these exposed squares losing clicks. Instead try to play moves that work with these at risk squares. I give a strategy for how to leverage at-risk squares in the \u201Cvirtual mines\u201D section of this guide. ")],-1)),e[168]||(e[168]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image33.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[169]||(e[169]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[170]||(e[170]=t("p",null," The above example shows a common mistake when dealing with exposed squares. We can see that the \u201C3\u201D is not part of any already revealed openings and is also not protected by any mines, so it has potential to lose clicks to a future opening. It might be tempting to go for an opening prediction on purple, but this would be a mistake. If purple gives an opening, then it\u2019s very likely that the opening will expand to also include the \u201C3\u201D which means that a click was wasted. ",-1)),e[171]||(e[171]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"Back to the review",-1)),e[172]||(e[172]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image34.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[173]||(e[173]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[174]||(e[174]=t("p",null," I\u2019ve shown the full board above to take stock of the full situation. This game has a very real chance of making it to 100%. We still have the region in the bottom left that we have been saving. We also have a nice enclosed region on the right hand side. We have done a manual density count and determined that there are 11 floating mines left in 36 floating squares which works out as a very high density of 30.56%. ",-1)),e[175]||(e[175]=t("p",null," We will focus on the right hand side next as it is the larger area (keeping the option open of using minecount on the left hand side). ",-1)),e[176]||(e[176]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image35.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[177]||(e[177]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[178]||(e[178]=t("p",null,"There are 4 moves worth considering here.",-1)),e[179]||(e[179]=t("ul",null,[t("li",null," Blue is the worst option as the density is very high, so it is much more likely to be an unnecessary risk than it is to give an opening. I\u2019ve included it though as it could be a decent move at lower densities. One can imagine that it would be very good at enclosing the board if it gave an opening. "),t("li",null," Cyan has a decent chance of being an opening. The drawbacks are that it has a [mine density]% chance of blasting and also the possibility of losing a click if green is an opening. "),t("li",null," Green has the strong benefit of being a safe square to click on. It can be an opening itself, although it also has the risk of losing a click if cyan is an opening. If it does not grant us an opening, then it has good follow-up options since it can be \u201Cpulled\u201D both upwards and downwards. "),t("li",null," Purple is a high-density type of move. It\u2019s a safe square to click on, although it is threatened by a possible opening to its bottom-right. The most likely follow-up to purple is that we start exploring the squares to its right, which may involve taking on extra risk depending on how lucky we get. ")],-1)),e[180]||(e[180]=t("p",null," I\u2019ll first compare cyan and green, and then I will come back to purple. Blue has been ruled out as it only makes sense on low density. ",-1)),e[181]||(e[181]=t("p",null," When playing by instinct, I would typically go for cyan, which is quite a natural move in lower density situations where green has the big risk of being ruined by the 50% chance of a mine being to its bottom-right. As this was a high-density and high-stakes situation, I examined the options more closely. ",-1)),e[182]||(e[182]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Cyan")],-1)),t("ul",null,[e[39]||(e[39]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of being a mine is 0.3")],-1)),e[40]||(e[40]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of being an opening (assuming it is safe) is 0.33"),t("p",null,[a(" This comes from the following expression where d is density: "),t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"(1 - d)^3")])],-1)),t("li",null,[e[33]||(e[33]=t("strong",null,"The chance of losing a click to an opening (assuming cyan is safe) is 0.18",-1)),e[34]||(e[34]=t("p",null," This comes from the below calculation (colours based on diagram below) ",-1)),e[35]||(e[35]=t("p",null,[t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"P(loses click given cyan is safe) = P(at least one mine in orange) * P(yellow safe) * P(red mine)")],-1)),e[36]||(e[36]=t("p",null,[a(" In terms of density this is: "),t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"(1 - (1 - d)^2) * (1 - d) * 1/2")],-1)),e[37]||(e[37]=t("p",null,null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image36.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[38]||(e[38]=t("p",null,null,-1))])]),e[183]||(e[183]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Green")],-1)),t("ul",null,[e[46]||(e[46]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of it being a mine is 0")],-1)),e[47]||(e[47]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of it being an opening is 0.24"),t("p",null,[a("This comes from "),t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"(1 - d)^2 * \xBD"),a(".")])],-1)),t("li",null,[e[41]||(e[41]=t("strong",null,"The chance of it losing a click to an opening is 0.12",-1)),e[42]||(e[42]=t("p",null,"This comes from the below (colours based on diagram below)",-1)),e[43]||(e[43]=t("p",null,[t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"P(green loses click) = P(yellow all safe) * P(red mine) = (1 - d)^4 * \xBD")],-1)),e[44]||(e[44]=t("p",null,null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image37.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"}),e[45]||(e[45]=t("p",null,null,-1))])]),e[184]||(e[184]=t("p",null," So, seeing these numbers, it should be very clear that green is better on all measures except opening likelihood. In fact, contrary to what the numbers above might suggest, green is also better when it comes to opening likelihood. ",-1)),e[185]||(e[185]=t("p",null,[a(" I\u2019ve been slightly deceptive in how I did these calculations. Whilst I stated that the chance of cyan being an opening is 0.33, this was conditional on cyan being safe. It would be better to look at the chance of cyan being an opening without necessarily assuming it is safe. When viewing it this way, the chance of cyan being an opening is "),t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},[a("P(cyan safe) * P(cyan is an opening given it is safe) = "),t("strong",null,"0.23")]),a(" . We had the equivalent figure of green being "),t("strong",null,"0.24"),a(" , so green is very slightly more likely to produce an opening than cyan. ")],-1)),e[186]||(e[186]=t("p",null," So green is better than cyan in all measures. I\u2019ll now compare green to purple. ",-1)),e[187]||(e[187]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Purple")],-1)),t("ul",null,[e[53]||(e[53]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of it being a mine is 0")],-1)),e[54]||(e[54]=t("li",null,[t("strong",null,"The chance of it being an opening is 0")],-1)),t("li",null,[e[48]||(e[48]=t("strong",null,"The chance of it losing a click to an opening is 0.11",-1)),e[49]||(e[49]=t("p",null,"This comes from the calculation below",-1)),e[50]||(e[50]=t("p",null,[t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"P(purple loses click) = P (yellow all safe) = (1 - d)^6")],-1)),e[51]||(e[51]=t("p",null,null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image38.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[52]||(e[52]=t("p",null,null,-1))])]),e[188]||(e[188]=t("p",null," So based on these numbers, I consider green to be better than purple. Purple is slightly less likely to lose a click than green, but green more than makes up for this as it has a 24% chance to give an opening (and even if it doesn\u2019t give an opening, it will still give great progress). ",-1)),e[189]||(e[189]=t("p",null,"So, we pick green and end up with the below.",-1)),e[190]||(e[190]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image39.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[191]||(e[191]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[192]||(e[192]=t("p",null," I\u2019d like to go on a bit of a tangent before returning to this situation. We are in a slightly precarious spot as there is a real chance we could lose some clicks to an opening. I\u2019d suggest staring at it a bit and thinking about how you would play it. ",-1)),e[193]||(e[193]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"A favourite pattern",-1)),e[194]||(e[194]=t("p",null," Can you really call yourself a minesweeper player if you don\u2019t have a favourite pattern? ",-1)),e[195]||(e[195]=t("p",null,"My favourite pattern for NF Efficiency is the below",-1)),e[196]||(e[196]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image40.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[197]||(e[197]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[198]||(e[198]=t("p",null," Once you first see this pattern, you will start seeing it in lots of different places. The move is to go for the green square as this is either protected by mines (left image below) or very likely to give an opening (right image below). ",-1)),e[199]||(e[199]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),t("div",f,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image41.png",class:"img-simple img-300 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"}),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image42.png",class:"img-simple img-300 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"})]),e[200]||(e[200]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[201]||(e[201]=t("p",null," I apologise for the slightly out of place section, I wasn\u2019t able to resist not including this. This pattern serves as a good illustration that moves can have multiple different ideas behind them. There\u2019s another short section, before I get back to the review, which I promise will be more relevant. ",-1)),e[202]||(e[202]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"Virtual mines",-1)),e[203]||(e[203]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image43.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[204]||(e[204]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[205]||(e[205]=t("p",null," I will show a technique that can sometimes be used when you have squares that are at risk of losing a click to an opening. In the above screenshot, we are at risk of there being an opening on the white square that would cause us to lose clicks on the purple squares. ",-1)),e[206]||(e[206]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image44.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[207]||(e[207]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[208]||(e[208]=t("p",null," The only way to prevent the bad opening is to have a mine in one of the orange squares. Assuming we are going for 100%, there absolutely must be (at least) one mine in these orange squares as otherwise we have lost. ",-1)),e[209]||(e[209]=t("p",null," We can consider the different cases where the virtual mine is in the top, middle or bottom orange square. It should be possible to see that in all of these cases, the green square will be protected. So, it is safe to click the green square. ",-1)),e[210]||(e[210]=t("p",{class:"text-h5"},"Back to the review",-1)),e[211]||(e[211]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image45.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[212]||(e[212]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[213]||(e[213]=t("p",null," Where we left off was that we were in a precarious position. If the white square (or the square below it) is an opening, then we will lose clicks. The only way to prevent the white opening is to have a mine somewhere in orange (below diagram). ",-1)),e[214]||(e[214]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image46.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[215]||(e[215]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[216]||(e[216]=t("p",null," Provided that we are still on track for 100%, there will be a mine in the orange squares and so the green squares will be protected and safe to click on. This is the same concept as the virtual mines discussed in the previous section. In the game, I clicked one of the green squares and this led to a surprising amount of progress. ",-1)),e[217]||(e[217]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image47.png",class:"base-img img-600 top-space",loading:"lazy"}),e[218]||(e[218]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[219]||(e[219]=t("p",null," We clean up the protected squares and end up in the above situation. We have 4 floating mines in 15 floating squares (26.7% density). ",-1)),e[220]||(e[220]=t("p",null," An obvious question to ask is - which region should we start with. Usually, the answer is to start with the larger region, however these regions are quite similar sizes. ",-1)),e[221]||(e[221]=t("p",null," There are two more factors we can take into account when deciding which region to go for: ",-1)),e[222]||(e[222]=t("ol",null,[t("li",null," How much benefit would the region get from having a more refined minecount. It can help to ask yourself questions such as: would I play the right region differently if I knew it had, say, 1 mine left vs 3 mines left. If a region would benefit significantly from knowing the minecount then it is better to leave it until last. "),t("li",null," How good are the guesses in this region. If a region has really good low risk guesses that are likely to solve the whole region, then it would suggest going for that region first. ")],-1)),e[223]||(e[223]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image48.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[224]||(e[224]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[225]||(e[225]=t("p",null," I\u2019ve labelled 4 candidate moves above. We have green and cyan in the left region. We have blue and dark green in the right region. Let\u2019s consider these moves with the factors discussed above in mind. ",-1)),e[226]||(e[226]=t("p",null," As I will explain in more detail later on, the left region has a very strong guess with green. Minecount helps a little bit as if we were told that the number of mines in the left region was low (0 or 1), we would go for cyan instead. The left region does have a lot of information available though, so it is likely we can solve it without needing the extra help from minecount. ",-1)),e[227]||(e[227]=t("p",null," The right region is quite tricky. If we guess green or blue, we may end up getting stuck if they do not reveal a nice number. Minecount would be very helpful here. Low density would tell us to go for blue and high density would tell us to go for green. Having a precise minecount in the right region could also help us in situations where our guesses don\u2019t yield direct logic. ",-1)),e[228]||(e[228]=t("p",null," With the above factors in mind, it makes sense to start in the left region taking the green guess, which is what I did in the game. ",-1)),e[229]||(e[229]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image49.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[230]||(e[230]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[231]||(e[231]=t("p",null," I\u2019d like to go into a little bit more detail about why the green guess is so good. The idea behind green is that we are hoping that there is a mine preventing the opening in one of the 6 orange squares. ",-1)),e[232]||(e[232]=t("p",null,[a(" A quick sanity check confirms that green is a low risk option. The naive calculation would be as follows: green loses clicks if the 6 orange squares are safe, and the density is 26.7%, so the chance of it losing clicks is "),t("span",{class:"inline-maths"},"(1 - 0.267)^6 = 15%"),a(". This calculation is wrong. Each extra square required to be safe further increases the remaining density so the true chance of green losing clicks is only 9% (this can be worked out with combinatorics). With this calculation, we can see that green is much safer than taking a 26.7% chance on a floating square. ")],-1)),e[233]||(e[233]=t("p",null," Usually most of the risks I take are from opening predictions as they tend to give better progress, however it is worth considering options like green as long as there is a clear idea behind them. The green squares provide a lot of information which should help us locate where the floating mines are in this region. It is a good idea to mentally play out the different situations of where the floating mines could be and whether we would be able to locate them. ",-1)),e[234]||(e[234]=t("p",null," For example, if we end up with something like the below image then we could click green and use the virtual mine method to locate which of the orange squares (hopefully) contains a mine. ",-1)),e[235]||(e[235]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image50.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[236]||(e[236]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[237]||(e[237]=t("p",null," With our green guess, we got very lucky. We were able to locate all 4 of the remaining mines without taking extra risk. I have marked one of the mines dark red as that would\u2019ve been a very natural guess in this region (corresponding to cyan earlier), so it is fortunate that we left this region until the end and played it carefully. ",-1)),e[238]||(e[238]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image51.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[239]||(e[239]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[240]||(e[240]=t("p",null," As we have found all of the floating mines, we can then solve the right region with zero risk taken and complete the board. ",-1)),e[241]||(e[241]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image52.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[242]||(e[242]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[243]||(e[243]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image53.png",class:"base-img img-400",loading:"lazy"}),e[244]||(e[244]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[245]||(e[245]=t("p",null,[a(" We are rewarded for our efforts with a shiny NF-Topaz and 4,500 shards for coming 2nd in the March 2024 championship (congratulations go to "),t("a",{href:"https://minesweeper.online/player/6836079",target:"_blank"},"Mikan"),a(" for coming first and also earning an NF-Topaz with his much faster game "),t("a",{href:"https://minesweeper.online/game/3193873310",target:"_blank"},"here"),a(" ). ")],-1)),e[246]||(e[246]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),t("div",m,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image54.png",class:"img-simple col-shrink",style:{width:"256px"},loading:"lazy"}),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image55.png",class:"img-simple col-shrink",style:{width:"310px"},loading:"lazy"})]),e[247]||(e[247]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Some miscellaneous tips</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> I have a few tips to mention here which I couldn\u2019t fit in any other part of the guide. <br data-v-d2d57a86><br data-v-d2d57a86> One important skill is to be able to play the start of games fast, as that means that you can go through boards more quickly so that you come across more boards which have potential. One way to go faster is to know when to break away from the core strategy. For example, you can sometimes skip out on clearing protected squares if you know that those protected squares won\u2019t give information that can change the best guess - you should just go for the best guess first. Also, when there are multiple similar guesses that are far away from each other, then unless the board looks very promising, it\u2019s not always worth spending much time weighing up which is better as you\u2019ll often end up having to do both guesses anyway, since information doesn\u2019t usually travel very far in NF efficiency (at least for expert density). </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> An advanced skill to learn is to know when to minecount. Sometimes it is even possible to make a judgement by eye, for example, if you\u2019ve revealed some very large openings and don\u2019t see many high numbers on the boards then it is likely that the remaining density is on the high side, which can lead to playing in a different way. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> It\u2019s very important to mentally track which squares are at risk of being on the edge of an opening, as if these squares get hit by an opening then you\u2019d know that you need to reset. There is a cheap trick for this, which is to take screenshots of at-risk squares, although I\u2019d encourage practising remembering these squares instead. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> How do you get a feel for how doable 100% NF expert is? I first got a feel for this by playing expert sized boards but with a lower number of mines, starting with 30x16/70 and then progressing on to 30x16/80, 30x16/90 and finally 30x16/99 (true expert), each size taking longer than the previous. I also recommend a similar strategy for other categories in minesweeper such as when trying to improve a time PB. </p><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Conclusion</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> I hope that I have succeeded in my goal of shedding some light on the more advanced parts of NF efficiency. In reviewing this game, I haven\u2019t shied away from positions which can be really close calls, and it is often hard to know what the objectively best move is. If you feel that there are things I have got incorrect in the guide or have other feedback then feel free to let me know on WoM ( <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/733893" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>llama</a> ) or on Discord (username llama7). If you found my guide helpful, I\u2019d appreciate it if you give it a \u2764 on the <a href="https://minesweeper.online/help/guides" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>guides</a> page. Special thanks go to janitor2 for giving me some very useful feedback when I was writing this guide. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The natural next step is to practise, so I\u2019d like to end this guide with some suggestions of NF efficiency challenges to try. </p><ul data-v-d2d57a86><li data-v-d2d57a86> Intermediate NF 100% - one of the easiest challenges. A skilled player should be able to win this around 1 in 7 times. A fun challenge is to try to complete Int NF 100% as fast as possible. This has heavy competition and is good training for recognising potential openings quickly in regular games. </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Expert NF 100% - the subject of this guide. I was the first person to achieve this back in <a href="https://minesweeper.online/game/801705135" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>2021</a> . As of writing this guide, 14 other people have got it. A special mention goes to <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/15420315" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>Yermak</a> who achieved it 3 separate times during the April 2026 championship. </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Hard NF 100% - the easier relative of expert. No-guess makes this a fun mode to play as it gives more friendly boards, and the start can be less frustrating due to the initial free opening. This was first achieved by <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/2677763" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>PTTACGfans</a> with this <a href="https://minesweeper.online/game/1139262670" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>game</a> . I\u2019ve come close with a 99% game that lost a single click at the end. </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Evil NF 100%. This is a considerable challenge, which I would estimate to be in the range of 2x-10x harder than expert NF 100%. As a no-guess game mode, evil brings with it some new highly interesting situations around using no-guess meta-reasoning. It has a slightly higher density than expert which can lead to a slightly different playstyle. I initially started this guide with the intention of motivating people to play Evil NF Eff, before I ended up getting it myself on <a href="https://minesweeper.online/game/3439056000" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>June 9th 2024</a> . I did a video review of my Evil NF 100% game <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wFJEG_dzr8g" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>here</a> (small warning - it is quite long and a bit rambly). </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Winstreak - trying to get as many 100% NF Eff wins a row. This can be a nice challenge as it allows a mix of playing fast and also slow + thoughtfully once a streak gets going. I played this when there were bounties running for Beginner and Intermediate. My record for beginner is <a href="https://minesweeper.online/winstreak/1517772914" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>21</a> . My record for intermediate is <a href="https://minesweeper.online/winstreak/1611609033" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>6</a> , which is possibly one of my hardest NF Eff achievements to beat due to the luck required. </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Mastery - this is not super popular, but there has previously been a <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1TyWG9TAMAzhkmtmUrbbl2f_qfbP0xfePlGtRrpTmRr4/edit?gid=550494028#gid=550494028" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86> competition </a> for winning the most 100% NF Eff intermediate games out of 100. My record is <a href="https://minesweeper.online/mastery/4538607293" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>21</a> (shows as 22 because one game was &lt; 100%). There is a bounty by <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/9412864" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>SandCrawl</a> for getting 22 mastery, which I think has been a bit overlooked and could be a good but achievable challenge for anyone with a solid understanding of NF efficiency. </li><li data-v-d2d57a86> Arena. Specifically, the challenge here is to beat the efficiency arenas, which require beating a set number of games with 100% efficiency. I consider this to be one of the frontiers of NF efficiency. It requires a high degree of skill in being able to quickly find good guesses at a range of different densities. It also requires the ability to play very fast with a very low misclick rate. As of writing, there are outstanding bounties for completing L6 and L8 efficiency arenas without flags (bounty spreadsheet <a href="https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1n0YfTQMpTSjUb6KD_ABr8RkUeNEzooAVSFu4w20zQKI/edit" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>here</a> ). The current best is L5 which was first achieved by <a href="https://minesweeper.online/player/6836079" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>Mikan</a> with this <a href="https://minesweeper.online/arena/3210932" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>arena</a> . My advice for NF Eff arena is to familiarise yourself with the different board sizes/densities that can occur and learn when to skip a bad board. </li></ul><p class="text-h5" data-v-d2d57a86>Appendix: Preparation guess analysis</p><p data-v-d2d57a86> Here I go a bit deeper into the theory behind preparation guesses at different densities. I\u2019ve included this in the appendix as it\u2019s not necessary for understanding the guide. It\u2019s quite a maths heavy section, and there is a decent amount of uncertainty in my conclusion due to the difficulty of comparing different types of progress (e.g. surviving vs finding openings). There may still be some value in seeing how I approach this. And I would love to hear if anyone has new ideas on how to weigh up the various strategies. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86> As a reminder, a preparation guess is when you take an additional risk with protected squares in order to improve a potential opening prediction guess. We\u2019ll revisit the example from earlier. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',14)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image16.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[248]||(e[248]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[249]||(e[249]=t("p",null," Here green is an opening prediction, and cyan is a preparation guess with a [mine density]% chance of blasting. We are considering whether it is better to go for the green guess or the cyan guess, and how this decision is affected by the mine density. ",-1)),e[250]||(e[250]=t("p",null," I\u2019ll break down these guesses by considering the initial risks that apply to each, and also what the chance of getting an opening is from each. There is a third factor which I consider to be very important, which is that guesses give progress even if they do not immediately lead to openings. This \u201Cnon-opening\u201D progress may be realised in the short term, if perhaps some information gained leads to better opening predictions a few moves later. \u201CNon-opening\u201D progress may also be realised much later if information gained only becomes useful when a lot more of the board is revealed. Either way, this type of progress is very hard to quantify, so it\u2019s not something that I will go into much with my analysis, though it is something that should be kept in mind when drawing conclusions. ",-1)),e[251]||(e[251]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Comparison of initial risk")],-1)),e[252]||(e[252]=t("p",null," When comparing risks, keep in mind that when going for 100%, losing a click and clicking a mine should be equally treated as losses. The below table shows the main risks that apply to green but not cyan and vice versa ",-1)),n(o,{flat:"",bordered:"","wrap-cells":"",separator:"cell",dense:"",class:"q-my-lg article-table"},{default:l(()=>[e[58]||(e[58]=t("colgroup",null,[t("col",{style:{width:"50%"}}),t("col",{style:{width:"50%"}})],-1)),e[59]||(e[59]=t("thead",null,[t("tr",null,[t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"Green Guess")]),t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"Cyan Guess")])])],-1)),t("tbody",null,[t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image56.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})]),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image57.png",class:"base-img img-100",loading:"lazy"})])]),e[56]||(e[56]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[a(" Green will lose a click if we have both of the below conditions "),t("ol",null,[t("li",null,"There is at least 1 mine in orange"),t("li",null,"All yellow squares are safe")])]),t("td",null,"Cyan will blast if red is a mine")],-1)),t("tr",null,[e[55]||(e[55]=t("td",null,null,-1)),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image58.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})])]),e[57]||(e[57]=t("tr",null,[t("td"),t("td",null," If cyan reveals a 2 (or 3) then a backup guess will be required such as purple, which has similar risks to the green guess (may lose a click if there is a mine in orange and all yellow are safe) ")],-1))])]),_:1}),e[253]||(e[253]=t("p",null," Take a moment to think about which of these initial risks is more likely to happen and how this might be influenced by board density. ",-1)),e[254]||(e[254]=t("p",null,[t("span",{style:{"text-decoration":"underline"}},"Comparison of opening likelihood")],-1)),e[255]||(e[255]=t("p",null," Similarly, the table below shows some opening predictions that apply to green or cyan. ",-1)),n(o,{flat:"",bordered:"","wrap-cells":"",separator:"cell",dense:"",class:"q-my-lg article-table"},{default:l(()=>[e[63]||(e[63]=t("colgroup",null,[t("col",{style:{width:"50%"}}),t("col",{style:{width:"50%"}})],-1)),e[64]||(e[64]=t("thead",null,[t("tr",null,[t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"Green Guess")]),t("th",null,[t("strong",null,"Cyan Guess")])])],-1)),t("tbody",null,[t("tr",null,[t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image59.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})]),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image60.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})])]),e[61]||(e[61]=t("tr",null,[t("td",null,"White can be an opening if all 5 yellow squares are safe"),t("td",null," If cyan reveals a 1 then white can be an opening if all 3 yellow squares are safe ")],-1)),t("tr",null,[e[60]||(e[60]=t("td",null,null,-1)),t("td",null,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image61.png",class:"base-img img-200",loading:"lazy"})])]),e[62]||(e[62]=t("tr",null,[t("td"),t("td",null," If cyan reveals a 2 (or 3) then a backup guess will be required which has a chance of producing an opening ")],-1))])]),_:1}),e[256]||(e[256]=t("p",null," Now that we have some idea of which factors affect each guess, it\u2019s worth running some numbers to see how much these matter at different densities. I\u2019ve included the image of where the guesses are again for ease of reference. ",-1)),e[257]||(e[257]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image16.png",class:"base-img img-300",loading:"lazy"}),e[258]||(e[258]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> The formulas below are for the initial risk of each guess (either blasting or losing a click). I\u2019m using the letter d to represent density. </p><div class="block-maths" data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of green = chance green is a mine <em data-v-d2d57a86>or</em> it is safe but loses a click to an opening<br data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of green = P(green is mine) + P(green is safe) * P(green touches opening)<br data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of green = d + (1 - d) * (1 - (1 - d)^2) * (1 - d)^5 </div><br data-v-d2d57a86><div class="block-maths" data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of cyan = chance cyan is a mine <em data-v-d2d57a86>or</em> it is safe but the next move blasts/touches opening (the next move is either green or going for a backup guess)<br data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of cyan = P(cyan is mine) + P(cyan is safe) * [P(Grey is empty) * P(Green is mine) + P(Grey not empty) * P(square to left of green is mine or loses click to opening)]<br data-v-d2d57a86> Risk of cyan = d + (1 - d) * [ (1 - d)^2 * d + (1 - (1 - d)^2) * { d + (1 - d) * (1 - (1 - d)^2) * (1 - d)^5 } ] </div><br data-v-d2d57a86><p data-v-d2d57a86> I\u2019ve plotted the initial risks below. The risk for the green guess is shown by the green line, and the risk of the cyan guess is shown by the blue line. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',8)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image62.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[259]||(e[259]=s('<p data-v-d2d57a86></p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86><a href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/dl0yjsafmf" target="_blank" data-v-d2d57a86>initial risk graph</a></p><p data-v-d2d57a86> We can see that the lines cross around 9% density, and after that the green guess has much less initial risk. We also note that around 20% density, the preparation guess (cyan) is almost 10% riskier than the border guess (green). So initial risk favours the preparation guess on very low density and the border guess on higher density. </p><p data-v-d2d57a86>Lets now do the same for the chance of each guess giving an opening</p><div class="block-maths" data-v-d2d57a86> Chance of green opening = P(green is safe) * P(green is opening)<br data-v-d2d57a86> Chance of green opening = (1 - d) * (1 - d)^5 </div><br data-v-d2d57a86><div class="block-maths" data-v-d2d57a86> Chance of cyan opening = chance cyan is safe and we get an opening after (either from green or from a backup guess depending on what cyan reveals) <br data-v-d2d57a86> Chance of cyan opening = P(cyan is safe) * [P(Grey is empty) * P(Green is opening) + P(Grey not empty) * P(square to left of green is opening)] <br data-v-d2d57a86> Chance of cyan opening = (1 - d) * [(1 - d)^2 * (1 - d)^4 + (1 - (1 - d)^2) * (1 - d)^6] </div><br data-v-d2d57a86><p data-v-d2d57a86> I\u2019ve plotted these below. The chance that green is an opening is given by the green line and the chance for cyan is shown by the blue line. </p><p style="text-align:center;" data-v-d2d57a86></p>',10)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image63.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[260]||(e[260]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[261]||(e[261]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},[t("a",{href:"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/mapherwcrl",target:"_blank"},"opening chance graph")],-1)),e[262]||(e[262]=t("p",null," We can see that the cyan guess tends to have around 2-3 percentage points higher chance of giving an opening than the green guess. This is what makes it so tricky to compare the two moves. For densities we are interested in (10% - 25%), the preparation guess has more initial risk, but a higher chance of producing an opening. ",-1)),e[263]||(e[263]=t("p",null," So a key question is how to weigh this up. How much is it worth taking extra risk (blasting/losing a click) for a higher chance of an opening? We do know that openings are incredibly valuable in NF Eff, as they are one of the best ways to make progress on a board. ",-1)),e[264]||(e[264]=t("p",null," One approach could be to look at the ratio between opening chance and risk taken. That is, for every 1% risk taken, how much chance of an opening do we get out of that. All we are doing here is dividing the chance of an opening by the initial risk of the guess. We should keep in mind that this approach isn\u2019t taking into account other forms of progress, but we can consider that later. In the next graph, I look at this ratio, again using a green line for the green guess and a blue line for the cyan guess. ",-1)),e[265]||(e[265]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},null,-1)),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image64.png",class:"base-img img-600",loading:"lazy"}),e[266]||(e[266]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[267]||(e[267]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},[t("a",{href:"https://www.desmos.com/calculator/eagwjtum0o",target:"_blank"},"opening/risk ratio graph")],-1)),e[268]||(e[268]=t("p",null," With this new graph, we can see that the crossover point has shifted upwards to 11% (recall that when we were just looking at initial risk, the crossover was at 9%). So if we purely consider the opening/risk ratio it would suggest taking the border guess (green) for densities above 11% and going with the preparation guess (cyan) for densities below 11%. ",-1)),e[269]||(e[269]=t("p",null," In reality, the crossover point will be higher. This is because the cyan guess gives better progress than green outside of what we have already considered with trivial openings. As an example, we could end up with something like the below on the cyan guess. ",-1)),e[270]||(e[270]=t("p",{style:{"text-align":"center"}},[t("br"),t("br")],-1)),t("div",y,[n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image65.png",class:"img-simple img-300 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"}),n(i,{src:"/img/articles/nf-eff-guide/image66.png",class:"img-simple img-300 col-shrink",loading:"lazy"})]),e[271]||(e[271]=t("p",null,null,-1)),e[272]||(e[272]=t("p",null," Whilst cases like this aren\u2019t accounted for in our formulas, it is clear that if we get something like this it would lead to further progress as we have some nice options for additional opening predictions. It\u2019s very hard to take into account all of the different ways that the cyan guess can give extra \u201Cnon-opening\u201D progress. ",-1)),e[273]||(e[273]=t("p",null," In the end it comes down to a judgement call for how much to value the extra progress from cyan. I would encourage you to think about how the information from the cyan square could help out in possible games, I won\u2019t go into this too much myself for the sake of brevity. ",-1)),e[274]||(e[274]=t("p",null," I\u2019ll give my judgement on this, although it\u2019s very subjective and unrigorous. I\u2019ll assume the board density is 15% for reasons that will become clear. On 15% density, we survive the initial risk of the cyan guess around 70% of the time which is split between 40% for getting an opening and for 30% for getting no opening. This is admittedly very handwavy, but my judgement is that the extra unaccounted for information given by cyan is probably equivalent to 4% chance of getting an opening. If we were to edit our opening/risk ratio graph to boost cyan\u2019s opening chance by 4% then we\u2019d see the lines cross each other around 15%. This 4% figure is basically pulled from the air though, I have considered lots of different ways that the cyan guess can give progress to reach this figure, however I expect that everyone will judge this differently. Given that boosting cyan\u2019s opening chance in this way changes the crossing point to 15%, then I would claim that you should go for cyan below 15% and green above 15%. However, the exact crossing point is very sensitive to how much cyan\u2019s opening chance gets boosted by, for example if we instead boost cyan\u2019s opening chance by 6% then the crossing point becomes 20% density. ",-1)),e[275]||(e[275]=t("p",null," There isn\u2019t any strong takeaway from this section, and indeed there is a lot of uncertainty in my conclusions. I\u2019ve mainly provided this to give some insight into how I view preparation guesses. It\u2019s worth keeping in mind that preparation guesses should always be treated with caution, there are no hard rules, and every situation is different. ",-1))],64))}});var x=r(w,[["__scopeId","data-v-d2d57a86"]]);export{x as default};
